    <center><h1>Music: The Simplicity and Complexity</h1></center>
    <center><h3>Intro</h3></center>
    <center><p>Music is something that is extremely versatile, yet can be as simple as playing one note. It is something that is very complex and most people don't take the time to really appreciate all that it can be. There are is an endless amount to the types of music that you can have, and even though these types can contain so much diversity they still have to power to bring people together. I once was told that "music is one of the very few things that links everything together. Not just the people in this room, but people across the planet." I know that all of this may sound cheesy, but hopefully an appreciation of music can be gained by someone by this project.</p></center>
    <center><h3>Simple Notes</h3></center>
    <center><p> <b>The definition of music is vocal or instrumental sounds that produce beauty of form, harmony, and expression of emotion.</b> There are just seven notes in music that are used to make up so many different songs. These notes are A, B, C, D, E, F, and G. Each note a step higher in pitch than the last. There are however, many different keys that these notes can be played in which will either mean that these notes could be much higher or much lower than a normal scale. They can also sound happy or sad based on which key these notes are played in; a major key which is happy sounding or a minor key, which is sad sounding. You can also make a note something called "sharp" or "flat" which is when you either make the note slightly higher than its original pitch if it is sharp. Or you make the note slightly lower than the original pitch if it is flat and these two things give an even bigger range to the amount of things that music can do. For example, if you took an A note and made it sharp it would be an A#.</p></center>
        <video height="250px" width="350px" controls>
        <src="videos/chromaticscale.html"> 
        </video>
        <p>this shows a short video of a chromatic scale</p>
